This code determines if all courses can be finished given prerequisite constraints using Kahn's algorithm for topological sorting (BFS-based approach). 
It builds a directed graph where an edge prerequisite → course means the prerequisite must be taken before the course, and computes the indegree (number of prerequisites) for each course.
Courses with zero indegree are added to a queue, and as each course is "completed," its outgoing edges are removed by decrementing the indegree of dependent courses, adding them to the queue when their indegree reaches zero. 
If the number of completed courses equals the total number of courses, true is returned (no cycle), otherwise false (cycle detected).

Time Complexity: O(V + E) — where V = numCourse and E = number of prerequisites; each vertex and edge is processed once.
Space Complexity: O(V + E) — for the adjacency list, indegree array, and queue.

import java.util.*;
class Solution {
    public boolean canFinish(int numCourse, int[][] prerequisites) {
        List<List<Integer>> graph = new ArrayList<>();
        for(int i = 0 ; i<numCourse; i++){
            graph.add(new ArrayList<>());
        }
        int[] indegree = new int[numCourse];
        for(int[] pre : prerequisites){
            int course = pre[0];
            int prerequisite = pre[1];
            graph.get(prerequisite).add(course);
            indegree[course]++;
        }
        Queue<Integer> q = new LinkedList<>();
        for(int i = 0; i< numCourse; i++){
            if(indegree[i] == 0){
                q.offer(i);
            }
        }
        int completed = 0;
        while(!q.isEmpty()){
            int curr = q.poll();
            completed++;
            for(int next : graph.get(curr)) {
                indegree[next]--;
                if(indegree[next] == 0){
                    q.offer(next);
                }
            }
        }
        return (completed == numCourse);
    }
}

